canonical:
  title: 謝勅祭國母表
  author: 韓曒如
  language: lzh
  text: 詔命及門存歿知感中謝 伏念臣積釁所及先妣奄殂遣單介以奔馳號昊天而訃告豈圖睿眷特降使華俾陳奠酹之儀以示哀榮之典顧無常檢出自殊私此盖伏遇皇帝恩信結於諸侯孝理形于四海以臣忠勤於事上恤臣痛切於喪親施及孤魂漏玆異澤誓更輸於誠愨永不負於慈憐
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 謝勅祭國母表
  author: 韓曒如
  language: lzh
  text: 詔命及門。存歿知感。中謝。 伏念臣積釁所及。先妣奄殂。遣單介以奔馳。號昊天而訃告。豈圖睿眷。特降使華。俾陳奠酹之儀。以示哀榮之典。顧無常檢。出自殊私。此盖伏遇皇帝恩信結於諸侯。孝理形于四海。以臣忠勤於事上。恤臣痛切於喪親。施及孤魂。漏玆異澤。誓更輸於誠愨。永不負於慈憐。
korean:
  title: 칙명으로 국모에게 제함을 사례하는 표
  author: 한교여
  language: kor
  text: |-
    조명(詔命)이 문(門)에 이르자 산 사람이나 돌아가신 이나 모두 감격할 줄 아옵나이다. 중사
    엎드려 생각하옵건대, 신이 죄가 쌓여 선비(先妣)께서 세상을 떠나셔 사신(使臣)을 보내어 달려가 하늘에 부르짖으며 부고(訃告)하였삽더니, 뜻밖에 황제께옵서 돌보시어 특히 사신(使臣)을 내리시어, 제전(祭奠)의 의식을 차리게 하시고 애영(哀榮)의 특전을 보이시니, 이는 상례(常例)에 없는 특별한 은명(恩命)이라 생각하옵니다.이는 대개 황제께옵서 은총과 신의로 제후(諸侯)들을 맺으시고 효리(孝理)를 사해(四海)에 나타내시어 신이 상국(上國)을 섬김에 있어 충근(忠勤)하다 여기시고, 신이 친상(親喪)에 애통이 심함을 어여삐 여기시어 베푸시는 은전이 고혼(孤魂)에까지 미쳐 이런 이수(異數)의 은택을 나누심인가 하옵니다.맹세하고 다시금 충성을 다하여 길이 인자하게 어여삐 여기심을 저버리지 않고자 하옵나이다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0370_010_0190&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: A Memorial in Gratitude for the Emperor's Rite of Sacrifice to the Empress Dowager
  author: Han Gyo-yeo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When the imperial edict reached our gate, both the living and the departed felt its grace.

    In reverent submission, I reflect: My accumulated transgressions hastened the departure of my late mother. I dispatched a lone messenger who rushed forth, crying out to heaven and announcing her passing. Yet unexpectedly, His Majesty's compassion turned toward us. He sent forth his envoy, permitting us to perform the rites of remembrance and bestowing upon us the honor of his imperial mourning.

    This exceeds all common precedent—it is a singular mark of his grace. It flows, I believe, from the Emperor's benevolence and trustworthiness toward all the princes of the realm, and from his manifestation of filial virtue across the four seas. He regarded my service to the imperial court as diligent, and seeing my grief for my departed parent, he extended his compassion even to the wandering spirit of the departed. Thus has this unprecedented favor descended upon us.

    I swear anew to repay this kindness with unwavering loyalty, and never to betray the imperial clemency that graces us.
  footnotes:
    - This is a formal court memorial (표, pyo) expressing gratitude for imperial recognition and rites performed for the author's deceased mother, the late Madame (先妣).
    - The phrase 'both the living and the departed felt its grace' reflects the traditional belief that imperial virtue extends to ancestors in the afterlife.
    - The 'four seas' is a classical expression referring to the entire realm under heaven.
